<HEAD>The Sea Stallion Helicopter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Copter Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sea Stallion helicopter that crashed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> early Monday, killing 22 of the 37 Marines aboard, is one of a family of heavy assault choppers with a reputation for good performance. CAPACITY: 55 soldiers, or cargo, plus a crew of four. DIMENSIONS: 67 feet, 2 inches long; 24 feet, 11 inches high. WEIGHT: Empty, 23,485 pounds; loaded, 42,000 pounds. RANGE: 540 miles. TOP SPEED: 196 mph. MANUFACTURER: Sikorsky Aircraft of <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. HISTORY: First ordered by the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 as a successor to the CH-53A, and used in the Vietnam War An advanced version, the CH-53E Super Stallion began service in 1981. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also use versions of the helicopter with differing model names and numbers. A similar model, the RH-53D Sea Stallion, was used in the abortive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission to rescue American hostages held in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.
