<HEAD>South Korean President Announces Referendum Delay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``The people...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT to ``foothold''
sted football. Pickup 9th graf `South Korea's...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> said Monday he is postponing a national referendum on his performance because `` violent leftist forces'' are trying to use it to overthrow the government. In an address on national television, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said `` it would not be of help to the country to hold a national referendum for my performance in office at this juncture.'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said the referendum, which had been widely expected sometime next month, will be held sometime in the future but he gave no date. The president had been expected this week to announce the date to keep a promise he made during 1987 presidential elections. It was not clear if <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> was backing away from the referendum because of concern about potential unrest or because he feared the government could not win the vote and might be forced into new elections. Some opposition and dissident groups had been demanding <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> stake his presidency on the referendum and step down if defeated. It is not clear if <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general, could win a referendum. The government had said earlier that <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would not step down if he were defeated, but some senior administration officials have conceded a defeat would put pressure on him to call new elections. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said anti-government forces were attempting to use the vote to organize violent protests and topple the government. Dissidents and radical students have organized violent demonstrations in recent weeks, but they have little popular support. `` The people are worried,'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said. `` Leftist forces are trying to use the referendum as a foothold to overthrow the free democratic system.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s divided opposition parties were split over <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s decision The Party of Peace and Democracy of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON> welcomed the decision, while the <ORGANIZATION> Reunification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young-sam </ORGANIZATION> said it would accept a temporary delay. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-sam </PERSON> had been pushing for a referendum after predicting <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would lose. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON> opposed a referendum, apparently because <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-sam </PERSON>'s party had overtaken his party in opinion polls and could win presidential elections. The two Kims are bitter rivals who split the opposition vote in December 1987 presidential elections, allowing <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> to win with 36 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> promised during the election campaign to hold a referendum after his first year in office to give voters a chance to evaluate his performance. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> also said `` national opinion'' was split on whether to hold the referendum. `` One opposition party said the referendum should be on the question of policy matters, while another party said it should be on a vote of no-confidence,'' he said. `` In view of these developments, the proposed referendum, originally intended to stabilize the political situation and solidify democratization, has lost its meaning,'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
