<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf `The person ...' to UPDATE with
report of teen-agers tossing stones at Proctor's car earlier Saturday,
punching and threatening him.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gunman who neighbors said was harassed regularly by teen-agers shot three young children at an apartment building Saturday and then wounded a police officer before being killed in a gun battle, authorities said. One of the children, <PERSON> Ivory </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 9, died at 9:50 p.m. Saturday in the trauma center of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>. She had gunshot wounds to the head, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, associate administrator of the hospital. Of the two other children, boys aged 8 and 12, one remained critical and the third was in stable condition at the hospital, <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said. The administrator declined to identify the children, citing the wishes of family members. `` We do n't have a motive yet,'' Police Chief <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Palardy </PERSON> told reporters at the scene of the shootings. `` It looks like some sort of disaster in there. A man appears to have gone berserk and started shooting.'' The gunman, identified as <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON>, in his 40s, died at 4:10 p.m. of gunshot wounds, said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Francois </PERSON>, assistant director of nursing at <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. `` The person that was involved, for whatever reason, became very antagonistic when he returned home this afternoon,'' said West Orange Mayor <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Spina </PERSON>, who visited the scene. Two witnesses, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, said they saw teen-age boys tossing stones at <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> earlier Saturday while he was driving in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, which borders West Orange. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON> left his car to confront the youths, and one of the teen-agers punched him in the face and threatened him. The three children who were shot apparently had no connection to the earlier incident, the witnesses said. Police said they had heard reports of that incident but would not say whether it was a motive in the shooting. One neighbor, a 15-year resident who said he went fishing regularly with the gunman, said <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON> had been physically and verbally harassed recently by teen-age boys in an increasingly drug-infested neighborhood. `` His mind probably just snapped,'' said the neighbor, who added that he would not give his name for fear of an attack on his family by neighborhood youths. `` He's a nice guy. ... It's a shame this had to happen to him.'' One witness, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gress </PERSON>, who lives across an intersection from the apartment building in this <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> suburb, said he was playing solitaire in his home shortly before 3 p.m. when he heard gunfire that `` sounded like firecrackers.'' <PERSON> Gress </PERSON> said when he looked outside, he saw a young boy by a parked car across the street screaming, `` The guy's a maniac.'' <PERSON> Gress </PERSON> said he then saw a police car pull up to the corner, and the gunman started shooting at the cruiser. He went to telephone police and when he returned to the window, the gunman was lying on the ground and the police officer also lay wounded on the ground. The police officer, who works for the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, was not seriously injured, <PERSON> Spina </PERSON> said. He was admitted in stable condition at <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON>. The officer was on a routine patrol of the neighborhood, which lies on the border of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> and the city of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, when he heard the gunshots and went to the scene, <PERSON> Spina </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Palardy </PERSON> said the identity of the officer was not immediately available. <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON> first started shooting at a woman in a first floor apartment, and police believe the gun misfired, allowing the woman time to run into the bathroom. The gunman then shot a child in the apartment and went outside, where he shot two more children, <PERSON> Spina </PERSON> said. The police officer hit the gunman with four rounds, officials Residents of the neighborhood said crime there has worsened recently, with older people forced to live in fear of drug-related violence. `` The young teen-agers are jumping people all the time,'' said <PERSON> Deidra </PERSON> <PERSON> Biggest </PERSON>, a 25-year-old resident who has lived in the area for eight months. `` Houses are getting robbed and cars are getting stolen.'' `` It's getting worse all the time,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorham </PERSON>, 26, who has lived in the area for six months. `` It's crazy out there.''
