soundman's death, CORRECTS name of justice of the peace. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers and leftist guerrillas fought near a power station on the outskirts of the capital early Sunday, several hours before voting began in the presidential election. Elsewhere, soldiers shot three local journalists at military checkpoints, killing two of them, officials said. Troops from the 1st Infantry Brigade and guerrillas battled near the power substation in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION>, radio reports said. The sounds of the pre-dawn battle could be heard in downtown <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Afterward, military helicopters circled overhead, occasionally firing rockets at rebel positions. No casualty report was immediately available, and it was not known whether the battle would affect voting in that area. The rebels have knocked out much of the electrical power in the capital and threatened to attack people who drive on the nation's highways in a bid to disrupt the election, which they are boycotting The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> is trying to retain power in the election with candidate <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON>, a former foreign minister who says he represents new leadership and dismisses charges of corruption and incompetence. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> by law can not run for re-election. The front-runner, according to the polls, is businessman <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, leader of the rightist and free market <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or Arena. That party, which in the past has been linked to rightist death squads, already holds a slim edge in the Salvadoran congress. Soldiers reportedly shot and killed a soundman from a local television crew early Sunday morning in eastern <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Preliminary reports indicated that <PERSON> Mauricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Pineda </PERSON>, 24, died when soldiers opened fire on the crew's vehicle at a checkpoint near <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, acccording to a newsman at Channel 12, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON>. The crew was traveling from <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION> province to the coastal city of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, 115 miles from the capital, <PERSON> Figueroa </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Late Saturday night, soldiers shot to death a news photographer and wounded his colleague at a checkpoint near <LOCATION> Ilopango </LOCATION> Air Force Base, officials said. Both men were Salvadoran free-lance photographers who worked regularly for the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The agency's <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> office declined to comment. Armed forces officials were not immediately available to comment on either shooting incident. Justice of the Peace <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguilar </PERSON> said troops who brought in the body of photographer <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Navas </PERSON>, 28, said the shooting occurred when the two men's motorcycle failed to stop at an air force checkpoint. The magistrate said soldiers radioed the next checkpoint and that troops there shot the two men when they again refused to stop. <PERSON> Navas </PERSON> was shot twice, in the back and the side. The judge said he found at least 22 spent rounds at the scene. The other photographer, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galdamez </PERSON>, 34, was shot once in the back and was in serious condition at <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rosales </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>.
