<FIRST>r w AM-Spring     03-19 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spring,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spring is Here: The Weather is Changing, So Are The People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The long, dreary wait for the end of winter is nearing its end as nature gradually edges into change. Human patience, also nearing its limits with winter, can draw encouragement from the spring equinox Monday. While the change of seasons is a gradual, often fitful thing, calendars usually list the solstices and equinoxes as unofficial markers of these transitions. `` The first day of spring is one thing, and the first spring day is another,'' observed the late <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>, aware that March weather can be fickle and also that the change of seasons can occur at markedly different dates in different parts of the nation. Even so, millions will welcome spring at 10:28 a.m. EST, the moment of the vernal equinox, when the sun crosses the equator on its apparent journey northward, according to astronomers at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. This, and the autumnal equinox in September, are the only two dates on which the sun rises directly in the east and sets precisely in the west, the Observatory reports. These directions were used to align the Great Pyramids in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> with an error equivalent to the thickness of a piece of string seen at a distance of six feet, said observatory spokeswoman <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleere </PERSON>. Ancient graves in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and temples in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> are also aligned to the equinoxes, she said. For the human mind, too, the change may be a point of alignment. `` Spring is a transition season when things change very rapidly,'' observed the late <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Landsberg </PERSON>, professor emeritus of meteorology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>. `` One major thing is apparently the change in light ... the most rapid increase in light intensity occurs between February and April,'' <PERSON> Landsberg </PERSON> explained, and this seems to affect human glands and internal reactions. Other fluctuations causing humans to react include `` rapid temperature changes in many places, sometimes highly irregular, changing from low to high to high to low again,'' said <PERSON> Landsberg </PERSON>, who researched the biological effects of weather. Poets and philosophers have lauded spring over the centuries with a curious mixture of cheer and woe, reflecting the differing reactions of humans to the stress of changing weather. As <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> observed of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s weather, `` it gets through more business in spring than in any other season. I have counted 136 different kinds of weather inside of 24 hours.'' This places stress on the body and, scientists are beginning to believe, the mind also. Human responses vary. Malaise, romance and even depression are among the reactions to these seasonal changes _ although so-called spring fever has been most widely identified with that vague feeling of disinterest, mind-wandering and restlessness. Nature writer <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Borland </PERSON> reflected on the seasonal change in the book `` Twelve Moons of the Year:'' `` There is something in a mild March day that can touch a man to the very quick of his being. Just what it is can not readily be stated, but it must be compounded of sunlight and air and warmth and an immeasurable mystery that is partly summed up by the word ` promise.''' `` When the first warm days of spring come, we all feel a desire to escape, to run away. It becomes difficult to concentrate on serious matters, and we experience indefinable, vague yearnings that disturb our psychic balance and have a bad influence on our professional activities,'' wrote Dr. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gauquelin </PERSON>, a French psychologist, in his book `` How Atmospheric Conditions Affect Your Health.'' `` Spring is a period when new romances start, when fresh plans are made ... But it is also a season when people experience frequent changes of mood and have bitter arguments with one another,'' <PERSON> Gauquelin </PERSON> wrote. His volume attributes people's response to `` spring hormonal crisis,'' when the endocrine glands are more active and sexual interest heightened. Whether the changes are the result of hormones, sunlight or other factors, nearly everyone observes and reacts to them. German studies in the 1960s found that most illegitimate conceptions tended to occur in May which, the researchers suggested, `` seems to indicate that spring may well be the season for all forms of impulsive behavior.'' On the darker side, French sociologist <PERSON> Emile </PERSON> <PERSON> Durkheim </PERSON> noted a half-century ago that suicides increase in the spring. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> studied the nation's suicide rates between 1969 and 1978 and found that during that decade `` the suicide pattern was distinctly seasonal, above average all spring and below average all winter.''
</TEXT>
