<HEAD>House To Consider Legislation On Minimum Wage, Protecting Whistleblowers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is making one of its slowest starts in recent memory as it heads toward April with little accomplished but a series of bruising internal battles. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will be on a two-week Easter break starting Monday, but before leaving Friday it confirmed Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> as defense secretary. The non-controversial ratification was a breeze after the bitter struggle over President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first choice for the job, former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>. The rejection of Tower by a 53-47 vote, largely along party lines, handed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a major defeat and absorbed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for nearly two months. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which does n't start its Easter break until Friday, faces floor votes this week on raising the minimum wage and legislation protecting whistleblowers _ government workers who report corruption within their own agencies. House members also may this week get a report from the <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. The 12-member committee, which undertook the inquiry into the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat's financial dealings nine months ago, began deliberating last week on whether <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> broke House rules. Their investigation coupled with the ill-fated fight to raise congressional pay, and now a search among Republican members for a minority whip, have sidetracked <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> action on any major legislation so far this session. House Republicans are expected to choose Wednesday between two candidates vying for the number two leadership post. Reps. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> are competing to succeed <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, who resigned last week after being confirmed as defense secretary. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> is the leader of an activist conservative wing of the party while <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>, currently the deputy whip, is regarded as a pragmatist who would probably be more willing to work with the Democrats to win support for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s programs. The House is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a bill to expand the rights of federal employees who blow the whistle on fraud. The measure sailed through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last Thursday, 97-0, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has promised to sign it after the House completes its work. Similar legislation was the subject of one of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s most controversial vetoes The legislation would lower the burden of proof for whistleblowers who claim they have been punished by their employers for disclosing misdeeds within their agencies, and increase the burden of proof for the federal agencies defending their decisions. House floor debate over the minimum wage is expected to begin Wednesday, with Democrats seeking an increase from $ 3.35 to $ 4.65 by 1992. Republicans are supporting the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal that minimum wages raise only to $ 4.25 by 1992, with a provision that employers be allowed to pay new workers $ 3.35 for the first six months. The minimum wage has not increased since 1981. Budget negotiators from both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are to exchange offers this week, with Democrats expected to push for military cuts equal to domestic spending cuts in the fiscal 1990 budget. Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he and <ORGANIZ