<HEAD>Key Speeches At Advisory Conference Stress Party Line, Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A major government advisory conference convened Sunday with speakers urging unity in solving <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s growing economic problems, setting the tone for a legislative session that opens Monday. The brief and businesslike opening session of the 2,081-member <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> emphasized working together under the leadership of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The somber theme was in sharp contrast to the conference's last full meeting in April 1988, which saw unprecedented lively debate and calls for democracy. Since then, however, overheated economic growth has produced chronic shortages, widespread corruption and annual inflation of 36 percent, causing a slowdown in both economic and political reforms. Conference Chairman <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiannian </PERSON> urged the delegates to share the government's concerns, offer their suggestions and dedicate themselves to finding solutions. Vice Chairman <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Weichang </PERSON>, who delivered a 13-page work report, called on the delegates to `` be ceaselessly diligent'' in pushing forward the government's economic policies. The speeches were greeted with only perfunctory applause by the delegates who attended the 80-minute session in the Great Hall of the People in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The conference draws delegates from among scientists, scholars, writers and official organizations. Its annual plenary session, scheduled to last 10 days, is always timed to coincide with the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature The congress begins its 16-day session Monday. Officials reportedly have attempted to discourage unwelcome debate and criticism of government policies at both meetings this year because of concern that the economic problems could trigger social instability. Conference official <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON> <PERSON> Siyuan </PERSON> reported that delegates have made more than 2,000 suggestions to the government since their last full meeting, and that more than a quarter of these have been adopted. But he gave no details about the nature of the suggestions. He said delegates have been briefed from time to time by officials on government policy and helped carry it out, especially by joining in efforts to police prices and cut back on wasteful construction projects. The speakers' clear message was that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s increasingly restive intellectuals can best serve the country by using their talents to implement party decisions rather than questioning or criticizing them. The opening session was attended by senior party and government leaders, including General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shangkun </PERSON>.
