<HEAD>1978 Sex Abuse Charge Still Follows Popular Columbus, Ohio, Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 12th paragraph, `In 1978...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The political wounds of a 10-year-old sexual assault allegation have been reopened for Mayor <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> with a city council probe and filing of a lawsuit that could mean the end of his hopes of running for governor. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> was <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> treasurer, a rising star in the local <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1978, when his children's 13-year-old baby sitter accused him of sexually assaulting her while she slept on a couch in <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>'s home. He has denied the allegation and a grand jury failed to indict him. But a newspaper story last fall resulted in the council investigation and one by the police department into whether a police officer spied on the girl's family in 1983 in an attempt to discredit her and gain a police endorsement for <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>, who was running for mayor. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> did n't get the endorsement, but he won the election. He is now serving his second four-year term as mayor of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s capital city. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>, 43, said he does not know how the resurrection of what has become known locally as `` the baby sitter incident'' will affect his political future, which he at one time had hoped would be spent in the governor's office. Once-plentiful rumors that <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> planned to run for governor in 1990 have died down since the investigations, despite an <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> poll in January that showed he had a 78 percent approval rating in the city of approximately 600,000. It was his highest rating ever. `` Part of me would love to -LRB- be governor -RRB-, but part of me says no. I've had a taste of politics that has not been good. The jury is still out in my heart and in my head,'' he said. The former baby sitter, <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Rae </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>, now 23, said she hopes <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>'s political future is indeed wounded. `` I do n't think <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> has any business being anywhere in politics, which includes governor,'' she said at a news conference on Wednesday. On Thursday _ two weeks after the council hearings _ Ms. <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>'s stepmother, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>, filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> against <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> and the police officer accused of spying, contending they engaged in a political conspiracy against the family In 1978, Ms. <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> told police that she was asleep on <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>'s couch when she awoke to find him performing oral sex on her She contended he then kissed her on the mouth, said he would be back later and walked out of the room. Ms. <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> later passed a police-administered polygraph test. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>, who was advised by his lawyer not to submit to a police test, said he passed a privately administered polygraph test. For 10 years, questions have surrounded the propriety of a <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury hearing into Ms. <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>'s allegations. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> was allowed to testify before the grand jury _ an opportunity that is only rarely afforded the accused in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Also permitted to testify on <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>'s behalf was a psychiatric expert who told the jury that, although he had not interviewed Ms. <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>, she may have dreamed the incident and believed it had actually happened. The grand jury declined to indict <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>. The `` baby sitter incident'' resurfaced last October when The Plain Dealer in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> reported that police officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, a devoted <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> supporter, had conducted secret, politically motivated surveillance on the <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> family for two months in 1983. After <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> was elected, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> was promoted from the police force to deputy city safety director and then deputy city development director. He was fired after he refused to cooperate in a police investigation a few days after the Plain Dealer story. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> says he knew nothing about <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s investigation or the officer's 13-page report of his findings until the newspaper queried <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> about it Oct. 7. He plays down the controversy surrounding <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s activities. `` We've had city employees who, unfortunately, have done things that are out of line. We've had worse stuff than this. We had a police officer who robbed banks,'' <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> said. The internal police investigation of <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION>, which ended in November, found no criminal activity, although police said their investigation was hampered by the fact that <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> refused to be interviewed. The findings of a council investigation _ which concluded March 2 after three days of testimony from <LOCATION> Rinehart </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> and others _ will be known next month. Testimony at the hearings raised questions about whether <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> knew of the report and who in the police department and his campaign may have authorized the surveillance. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, who testified under a grant of immunity, said he conducted the surveillance with neither the knowledge nor permission of his superiors, <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>, or any member of the <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> campaign. `` I did n't feel they had a need to know,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. He testified that he researched the <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> family's geneological history, recorded license numbers of mourners at the funeral of Miss <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>'s father in 1983, and obtained information on the family's banking records without obtaining a subpoena _ an order required under federal bank right-to-privacy laws <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said he conducted the investigation on city time and used city equipment. <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON>'s testimony that he did n't know about <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s report until last fall was contradicted by testimony from two local reporters, who told the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> they had confronted <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> with a copy of it in 1983. A third said he'd seen a copy of the report in 1983. The Pardue lawsuit seeks unspecified compensatory and punitive damages as well as preliminary and permanent injunctions ordering the defendants to halt any further investigation of the family. No hearing date was set.
