its actions in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, which it claims has been part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s territory since the 13th century. Many Tibetans say they enjoyed de facto independence before <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> communist troops entered in 1950. They accuse the Chinese of human rights violations and of trying to destroy <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s Buddhist-based culture The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed its resolution Thursday about the martial law <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> imposed March 8 after three days of anti-Chinese violence in the Tibetan capital, <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>. At least 12 people were killed in the fourth bloody Tibetan-Chinese confrontation in the past 18 months. The Parliament also appealed to foreign ministers of the 12-member <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> to offer their mediation. `` We are firmly opposed to and will by no means accept'' such mediation, the Chinese statement said. `` No foreign government, organization or individual is allowed to meddle in the question of negotiations between the Chinese central government and the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>.'' The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> is a self-exile many Tibetans consider their temporal and spiritual leader. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which also acted Thursday, has approved non-binding resolutions in the past urging the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to pressure <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to end alleged human rights violations in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. Two days after <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> imposed martial law on <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement of concern, which <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> dismissed as interference. `` The Chinese government is entirely justified and above reproach in taking the necessary measures to uphold law and maintain order,'' the Chinese legislative committee said. It reiterated <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s willingness to hold talks with the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, but ruled out independence or autonomy for the remote region. `` We strongly demand that the European parliament immediately stop its interference in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal affairs so as to prevent doing any harm to our bilateral relations,'' it said. It similarly warned the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to act in the `` interests of safeguarding Chinese-U. relations.''
