<HEAD>Son of Last King Recognizes Republic, Wants to Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The son of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s last king for the first time recognized the republic, renewing a campaign for him and his son to be allowed to return from a 43-year exile despite a constitutional ban, media reports said Sunday. In a letter to Italian president <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossiga </PERSON> published in Italian newspapers, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> wrote from exile in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> that he is not, however, renouncing his claim to the former throne of the House of Savoy. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON>, 51, wrote the letter Saturday, the sixth anniversary of the death of his father, King Umberto II. `` I want to do today what my father was not in a position to do, and that is to recognize this incontrovertible reality that is the Italian republic,'' he wrote. He said he was appealing especially on behalf of his 17-year-old son, <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Filiberto </PERSON>, whom he hoped would be allowed to attend an Italian military academy and university. The letter sparked immediate speculation that <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> was relinquishing his claim to the throne, but he quickly denied that was the case. `` I want to return to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> as soon as possible,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> Milan </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Corriere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Della </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sera </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` I say simply that I recognize the republic because it's there. I will never, never renounce my royal prerogatives. I am totally monarchist.'' <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> has appealed in the past for the government to allow his family to return. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s 1947 constitution, however, bans the entry of <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> and his heirs from the country and would need a two-thirds majority in both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to be altered. <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> reigned for 26 days before being forced into exile in 1946, when Italians voted by a slim margin to abolish the monarchy. <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> died in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in 1983 at the age of 78. In 1987, the government lifted the constitutional ban on the entry of his widow, the ex-queen <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON>. She has since returned to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> on a few occasions, but continues to live in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The House of Savoy ruled <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> for nine centuries and its kings reigned in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> from 1861 to 1946.
