<HEAD>First Family Observes Palm Sunday at Church Near White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President and Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> observed Palm Sunday by attending a worship service at an landmark Episcopal church a block from the White House. They knelt with other worshippers at the altar rail of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> and received Holy Communion at the 8 a.m. service At the conclusion of the service, they were given traditional palm fronds. The Bushes, who are Episcopalian, frequently attended the church during the eight years of his vice presidency. It was founded in 1815 and every president since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> has worshipped there. They were greeted at the church by the Rev. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, one of the rectors, who said, `` Congratulations on the puppies.'' It was a reference the six puppies born over the weekend to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s springer spaniel.
