<HEAD>Pilots Who Saw Combat Don't Think Lorenzo's So Tough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot laughed when asked why he is willing to risk his job in the showdown between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and its unions. `` For five years, every time the little guy with the rifle walked by, he made me bow down,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON>. `` I came out of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> with my head held up, and I'm not going to spend the rest of my life looking down when I pass other pilots.'' He is among the 3,400 Eastern pilots who stunned management by joining the March 4 walkout by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union. He's also a former prisoner of war. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> 1st Lt. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON>, piloting an F-4 Phantom fighter on a bombing mission to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, was shot down Aug. 23, 1967. Five years and five months later, <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> was flown out of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> on a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> transport plane. He carried with him the wounds of years of torture and mistreatment that led to broken ribs, damaged joints, hepatitis and repeated bouts with dysentery. He also carried out a changed philosophy of life. `` Little things in life do n't bother you so much,'' said <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON>, 46. `` You want to stand up and be counted if someone is trying to take advantage of people and trying to force his ideas and views on them.'' Eastern, which had hoped to keep at least 25 percent of its pre-strike schedule of 1,040 daily flights during the strike, is struggling to maintain 10 percent, with the walkout well into its third week. The executives put in place three years ago by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> admitted they badly overestimated the number of pilots who would keep flying Only about 200 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots have crossed the picket lines. Pilots often have ignored the picket lines of other airline unions, but the Eastern pilots say they learned from <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> pilots, who lost their union along with the Machinsts in 1983 even though the pilots did n't honor picket lines. The pilots also say they believe that <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> also owns <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, is bent on stripping Eastern of its assets while chipping away at employees' pay and work conditions. Pilots union spokesman <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said another key to understanding the Eastern pilots' resolve is that 75 percent or more are military veterans, many with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> experience. `` One of the problems is this management has been trying to use intimidation and coercion,'' said <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>, a B-52 pilot who flew <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> combat missions in 1969. `` It speaks to the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> philosophy and shows how badly he misunderstands these pilots. `` These people know what it really is to be afraid; they've put their lives on the line in a hostile environment,'' <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said. `` If I survived <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, I damn sure am not going to be concerned about a guy putting memos on a bulletin board.'' <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> said as much as he loves flying and the lifestyle of a pilot for a major carrier, the job's not worth giving in to `` demeaning management.'' He recounted his <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> experience last week, talking by telephone from his <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> financial consulting office where he works when not walking picket lines. He was in one of the first bombing missions into <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> when he was shot down. <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> and his co-pilot ejected about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> and he could hear bullets pinging the parachute's canopy as he fell. They were captured when they landed, stripped of their clothes and marched to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>. Most of his imprisonment was in the infamous `` Hanoi Hilton.'' `` It started as soon as I got there. It was just like everything you ever heard about: beatings, ` rope tricks' where they tie you up and put stress on different joints, like a variation of the rack. `` At times you wonder if you will die there. But you have to have hope. That's all you have left,'' <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> said. He was freed in January 1973 as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> was winding down, and by that August, he was flying for Eastern. Shortly afterward he was laid off because of cutbacks because of the energy crisis, and he got an MBA from <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> said his Eastern salary is below the $ 70,000 to $ 75,000 average the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> estimates Eastern pilots earn annually. He said given the education and skills the pilots have, they resent <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and other managers' efforts to put them `` near the bottom of the barrel'' in the industry. `` Basically, I look at it that he's trying to destroy -LRB- employees' -RRB- way of living,'' <PERSON> Gerndt </PERSON> said. `` Why would I want to work for a man like that?''
