<HEAD>Government Urged To Tell All About Flight 103 Bomb Warnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Demands for an independent inquiry into <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s handling of warnings received before the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 will grow until the government explains its actions, an opposition party leader said Sunday `` We can not afford ` bag it and bin it' policies of British official secrecy on matters of security which affect every air traveler across the world,'' said <PERSON> Paddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashdown </PERSON>, leader of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Transport Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> `` must come clean on all the circumstances surrounding the advance warning,'' <PERSON> Ashdown </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Unless he comes to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> at the earliest opportunity next week and is competely candid in every detail, the demand for an official inquiry on both sides of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> will become irresistible,'' he said. Those demanding an independent inquiry include the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and relatives of those killed when Flight 103 exploded over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, Dec. 21 on a flight to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Investigators say the disaster, in which 259 died aboard the plane and 11 on the ground, was caused by a bomb concealed in a radio-cassette player packed in luggage in the plane's hold. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said Sunday he told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> `` as much as it is in my power to tell.'' Government ministers `` should not go around revealing things that might be against the national interest,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said he welcomed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>'s decision to send top aides to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to assess aviation security <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said he wants his officials to determine, among other things, when and how warnings were made against <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flights last year. `` The investigators have been working extremely closely with the Americans at all stages, and I think if they come over here, and the investigators have further talks with them, that can only be a very good thing,'' <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said. `` There is keen public concern in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and in this country about the progress of this investigation and it's not surprising that people should wish to come over and have further talks.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> confirmed last week it prepared a warning dated Dec. 19 that included photographs of a bomb hidden in a radio-cassette player but did not mail it until after Christmas. <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> has said the letter was of little importance because similar information had been sent out a month earlier by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and changed planes at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> before setting out for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Two <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> newspapers, The Observer and The Sunday Telegraph, reported Sunday that the Dec. 19 warning carried several important details that would have helped security people spot a rigged radio-cassette player.
