<HEAD>Killing of Congressman Underscores Cult of Political Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The assassination of a congressman shows the cult of political violence still haunts the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, despite President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s vow to end `` rule by the bullet.'' Rep. <PERSON> Moises </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON>, 55, a member of a pro-Aquino party, was shot to death Friday with two other people after arriving in the airport in his home province, <LOCATION> Masbate </LOCATION>, after a flight from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> 240 miles away. No arrests have been reported. But <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> newspapers quoted relatives as speculating that <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON>, from an influential political family, was slain by business or political rivals. He was the first congressman slain since Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> came to power in 1986 after a civilian-military uprising toppled President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. He was vice chairman of the public order and security committee in the House of Representatives. `` This is something we in public life have to expect in our job, especially in the kind of politics we still have,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> after the <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON> killing. <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> was critically injured 16 years ago during a bombing at a political rally in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. During a speech in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in November 1986, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> boasted that her `` people power'' administration had replaced `` rule by the bullet with rule by the ballot.'' However, <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON> is the latest in a lengthening list of politicians, journalists, human rights lawyers, municipal officials, and labor leaders slain in unsolved political killings during the <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> administration. The victims include Local Governments Secretary <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrer </PERSON>, who was gunned down near his home in August 1987. <PERSON> Ferrer </PERSON> became the first Philippine Cabinet member slain while in office. Others are labor leader <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Olalia </PERSON>, kidnapped and murdered in November 1986; leftist leader <PERSON> Lean </PERSON> <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON>, slain in September 1987; and <PERSON> Vicente </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerochi </PERSON>, a senior official of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION>, who was ambushed near his home last month. More than 90 people, including about 40 candidates, were killed in political violence during the campaign for January 1988 regional elections. About 50 people died in campaign violence before May 1987 congressional balloting. The military says such violence was worse during the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> years, and it often blames killings on Communist rebels. Indeed, the rebels have claimed responsibility for killing hundreds of police, soldiers and low-level officials in the last three years. But many Filipinos believe most killings of politicians have been the work of political rivals. `` If there is an outstanding truism about Filipino political life, it is this: Politically motivated murder is not meant to be punished,'' said the independent <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. `` In fact, what exists are the trappings of government without its essence. We have laws that are all too frequently _ and with total impunity _ violated.'' Killings of political figures, which grab headlines, also seem to go hand-in-hand with a general lawlessness that the government has been unable to contain. Last year, about 3,700 killings were reported in greater <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, which has a population of about 8 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION> reported in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week that of 26 journalists killed last year in the line of duty, five were in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Most of the Filipino journalists slain last year had reported on illegal gambling and other corruption in the provinces. By comparison, war-ravaged <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> registered four killings of journalists in 1988.
</TEXT>
