<SECOND>AM-Detroit-Homeless,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Unimpressed By City's `Warming Center' Ordinance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Outside Homeless, which subs for AM-DC-Homeless on AM-News
Advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KOLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers frequently detail the plight of the nation's homeless. <PERSON> Aldo </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> does n't read the papers _ he sleeps in them on Third Street. White, hardened by years of begging, either is mute or chooses not to speak. He communicates with fierce brown eyes and with the cane that props him up on his only leg. One tap means `` no;'' two taps mean `` yes.'' When White is asked whether he will benefit from a city ordinance ordering the opening of a vacant building to the homeless, he stares down at his stub and taps once. White is one of the thousands of homeless who wander the streets of the nation's sixth-largest city as officials try to find them shelter. Their challenge: providing it without jeopardizing <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s economic rebirth. The relationship between advocates for the homeless and Mayor <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> A. Young frequently has been stormy. Both sides disagree on the numbers of the city's shelterless. Advocates insist there are 10,000 to 60,000 others like <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a statistic disputed by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s press secretary. `` That's absurd,'' he said. `` If you go out and check the shelters, you'll see that most of them are half empty. There's not a single case this winter of somebody not having a place to spend the night.'' The ordinance that went into effect March 10, requiring <PERSON> Young </PERSON> to designate a vacant public building or rent a private one as a `` warming center,'' is a scaled-down version of a measure that would have opened 39 downtown buildings to the homeless. Young vetoed the more expansive plan, saying it would cost $ 2 million and threaten <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s convention business. The City Council, which proposed the ordinance, fell short in an attempt to override the veto. The warming center opened last week in a recreation building on the city's east side. No homeless showed up because word had n't yet spread on the streets, the shelter's operators said. Meanwhile, community leaders speculated about the impact of <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s veto on his widely expected run this fall for a fifth four-year term. <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit-Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> of the Homeless, said her group is urging the homeless it aids to register to vote. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> knows the anguish of homelessness. A year ago, her landlord evicted her and her five children after the family could n't afford to pay its gas bill. `` I went from shelter to shelter,'' she said. `` My family called me the Shelter Queen. When the mayor says -LRB- the original ordinance -RRB- would have cost $ 2 million, he's admitting there's a terrible, desperate need.'' Last week _ while the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> debated the merits of its housing plan _ <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>, who heads the state's welfare agency, urged officials to set aside part of the $ 500 million spent annually on temporary housing in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and invest it in a more permanent solution. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, a coalition aimed at improving the quality of life in the city, agrees. `` Putting the homeless in public buildings does n't solve the problem,'' he said. `` Ten years ago, homeless were derelicts with <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> jackets and wine bottles hanging out of their pockets. Now, they're women and children. `` You need permanent public housing. Otherwise, as soon as it's warm, they're back on the streets again. Young's veto of the original homeless plan probably wo n't backfire on him politically because it was replaced by the modified measure, <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> said `` The mayor sees the need and he's done something about it,'' he said.
