<SECOND>AM-Shipwreck Search,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explorer Plans to Plumb Boston Harbor for 18th-Century Shipwreck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> was 12 years old, he read about an 18th-century French ship that sank in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. Twenty years later, he has received permission to search for the wreck and its reputed riches. After researching the journals of French soldiers and other documents, <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>, 32, a construction worker from <LOCATION> Hopkinton </LOCATION>, believes the ship contains between $ 50 million and $ 500 million in gold coins and other cargo. `` It's like reliving a childhood dream,'' said <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>, who read about the Magnifique in an <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> Snow book, ` Shipwrecks Around <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>.' `` Back then, it might not have been that easy to do but with the technology we have now, it's possible.'' Last fall, the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaelogical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> approved <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>'s request to search for the Magnifique, a French vessel that ran aground near the end of the Revolutionary War. <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> plans to begin initial work on the site within a few days. The 218-foot ship may have been carrying up to 500 soldiers when it sank in August 1782, said <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>. The wooden vessel was weakened by a tour of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> where a parasite called the teredo had eaten away at its hull. <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> said his research could not uncover whether men died when the ship sank in less than an hour or if they were ferried to safety. `` The French were very secretive about their navy back then,'' he said. <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> said records culled form the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and the Journals of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> soldiers allude to a cargo that may have included 300,000 pistoles _ French gold coins that were also called <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> d'Ors. Last year, <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> and his team dove with a magnetometer, which detects magnetic metals, and a sonar system, which uses sound waves to detect objects, and found a large mass they believe to be the wreck. They believe the ship is under 20 feet of water and buried under 5 feet of sand and mud. <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> said the currents have changed over the years and the mud is now washing off the Magnifique, exposing it. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mastone </PERSON>, associate director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaelogical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>'s plan is the second one involving a search in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, the nation's filthiest harbor <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, who found the wreck of the Whydah off the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> coast several years ago with artifacts estimated at $ 40 million, has received initial permission to search for the crates of tea thrown into the harbor during the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> before the Revolutionary War. `` It's like people are just finding out there's a lot out there,'' said <PERSON> Mastone </PERSON>. <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON> is working with a crew of seven, including three divers. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cembrola </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION>, is in charge of cataloging any items retrieved from the wreck. `` I called my best friend from 20 years ago and told him about it,'' said <PERSON> Blasczak </PERSON>. `` He could n't believe I was actually doing what we talked about so long ago.''
