<HEAD>Family Of Woman Files $1 Million Lawsuit Claiming Botched Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A family has sued a cemetery for $ 1 million, claiming that a damaged casket allowed mourners to see the deceased's foot and a cemetery employee interrupted the funeral to demand that the rabbi move his car. All of this happened at the funeral of <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON> last year, family members said in a lawsuit filed in <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last week. Her husband, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>, and her two daughters and their families are seeking the damages from Menorah Gardens and Funeral Chapels for putting them through an emotional wringer at the funeral in January 1988. Menorah Gardens funeral director <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON> said through a spokesperson that he knew nothing about the lawsuit. `` It was a terible, terrible thing,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` We are looking forward to our day in court. Mrs. <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> and other relatives declined to discuss details of the case on the advice of their attorney. The lawsuit said the grave site was `` prepared in a sloppy and unkempt manner'' and chairs were filthy and rusty, and the scaffolding was uneven and covered with artificial carpet.'' This caused mourners to `` trip and stumble,'' the lawsuit said. Pallbearers were supposed to carry the casket from a hearse to the grave site. Instead, `` slovenly attired and unclean'' cemetery workers did so until family members insisted on completing the task themselves. During the service, a cemetery worker demanded that the rabbi move his car from a designated parking area, the lawsuit said. When the rabbi continued with the service, the employee wrapped a chain around the bumper of the rabbi's car and `` a backhoe or other piece of heavy equipment backed within close range of the automobile.'' As the casket was being lowered, it slipped as it was being placed in a vault. Two lids popped open, exposing the deceased woman's foot with a white tag attached to it, the lawsuit said. The casket would not fit in the vault and the straps supporting the casket could not be removed without more jarring of the casket and prying it with iron bars, it said. In June, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON> ordered a tombstone and specified that, for religious reasons, it should not be placed atop his wife's grave until Nov. 18. He and one of his daughters asked to see Mrs. <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>'s grave but were told that the original marker had been chewed up by a lawn mower, according to the lawsuit. In September, <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON> visited his wife's grave and found that her headstone was on it, contrary to his wishes.
