<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterand </PERSON>'s governing Socialists emerged the big winners Sunday in the second round of municipal elections, winning control of several large cities from the conservative and center-right parties. Early results showed such conservative bastions as <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mulhouse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dunkirk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Blois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Avignon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Quimper </LOCATION> falling into Socialist hands. Frequently city elections have been used to criticize the national government, but this year results seemed to confirm the leftist trend that re-elected <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> last spring and gave him a leftist majority in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is the first time that we have seen a government receive a powerful, popular encouragement during the municipal elections,'' said Interior Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Joxe </PERSON>, a Socialist. The second round was required in 832 towns and cities larger than 3,500 where no candidates won more than 50 percent of the vote in last Sunday's first round. Turnout in the ninth election in less than a year was estimated at between 72 and 73.5 percent. A national projection by the TF1 television network showed the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies winning 78 cities with populations above 30,000, compared to 66 in 1983 municipal elections. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won mayoral seats in 48 cities, compared to 53 six years ago; the conservative Rally for the Republic won 45 big cities compared to 47 in 1983; and the center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION