<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police using tear gas and rubber bullets clashed with about 100 youths who threw bottles and rocks in a protest against <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>'s chronic shortage of inexpensive housing. One police car was set ablaze by a gasoline bomb and some store windows were broken in the riot Saturday night in downtown <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, but no one was injured or arrested, police said Sunday. The protest began peacefully but turned violent when police briefly detained a youth who was caught painting slogans on a wall. Police said the riot, the city's worst in recent years, caused more than $ 125,000 in damage. It was the third time in a month that demonstrations against the shortage of low-rent apartments in the city have become violent.
