<HEAD>New Army Helicopter Unfit For Battle: Memo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new high-tech Army attack helicopter has broken down so many times that one commander complained the craft is less fit for battle than a 1960s vintage chopper, according to a report published Sunday. In a recent exercise, all 12 of the AH-64 Apache helicopters involved were incapacitated at least once within five days, according to internal <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> memos obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. The problems have prompted Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, whose staff obtained the memo, to call for an investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is unbelievable that we are fielding overly sophisticated and outrageously expensive weapons systems for our fighting men which simply do n't work,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said in a letter demanding the probe. The Army has received 450 of the AH-64s, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, for $ 13.4 million each, and plans to buy total of 975, spending $ 13.6 billion for the deal. Army and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> officials dispute allegations the helicopter is a hopeless case and defend its reliability. But in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> memo, Col. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, commander of the 82nd Aviation Brigade at Ft.. <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was highly critical of the AH-64, saying that for now at least he'd prefer to fly the AH-1, an updated version of Be