<HEAD>Asian Natural Disasters Linked to Environment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> suffered a terrible year of natural disasters in 1988 stemming in part from environmental destruction, especially deforestation, according to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> report made available Sunday. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> chronicled massive flooding in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and drought in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. It linked the natural disasters with general environmental ravages, especially large-scale deforestation. `` The phenomena of floods, mudslides, even earthquakes can be directly related to deforestation,'' the report said. The commission, which described 1988 as `` a terrible year,'' said major environmental problems faced by <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries included soil erosion, loss of deserts and industrial pollution. The report was included in an annual survey of the region. It will be presented at the organization's yearly conference, which begins in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on March 27. More than 1,000 delegates are expected to attend the 10-day meeting. The group has urged that development strategies take into account environmental factors.
