anding this weekend That distinction belonged to the space shuttle Discovery. But <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Minerva </PERSON> <PERSON> Esquivel </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION> recently from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, went out of their way for the event, even bypassing a hometown turnoff on Highway 58 that would have taken them right to the shuttle's landing site at <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're kind of discovering <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. We figured it was either the space shuttle or the swallows,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Esquivel </PERSON> said. Despite the high expectations, however, on Sunday television camera crews had to resort to throwing pebbles at the mission walls to get the birds to take flight for the proper dramatic effect. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Chauncey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> craned a home video camera around and around, looking for at least one good swallow flight to record. `` I'm not disappointed. Why be disappointed? I've got my health. It's nice weather. And I might get some good pictures,'' <PERSON> Chauncey </PERSON> said. At least one bird-watcher said the swallows actually got a one-month head start on the tourists. The first of the birds reached <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in February from their winter homes in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wohlgemuth </PERSON>, a birder with the <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION>. The birds' numbers at the mission have dwindled in rece