<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct cycle designator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman once considered terminally ill by doctors is cancer-free after receiving an experimental, four-organ abdominal transplant, hospital officials say. <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, 40, was admitted to Presbyterian-University Hospital of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> on Jan. 12 with an inoperable tumor on her liver bile duct. The following day, surgeons replaced her liver, pancreas, duodenum, and two sections of her small intestine. Her stomach was removed but not replaced, requiring her to eat six small meals a day spaced an hour or two apart. Ms. <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, a computer operator from <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, headed home free of malignancy Saturday, hospital officials said. She is among 11 once-terminal patients who are cancer-free after having four of their abdominal organs replaced. Ms. <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> said the transplant has given her `` a new lease on life.'' `` Now I have all the hope in the world,'' she said, adding that she must return to <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> in two months for a check-up. The transplants, believed to be the first of their kind, have been performed on 10 men and three women since June at <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian-University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Two patients died.
