<HEAD>Prototype Of Unique Aircraft Successful In First Test Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two test pilots took a successful 15-minute test flight Sunday in a prototype of a revolutionary aircraft designed to perform like both a helicopter and an airplane, officials said. The V-22 Osprey, the world's first production tilt-rotor aircraft, remained in helicopter mode throughout the flight, according to officials of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of two companies which built the craft. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials described tests in aircraft mode as `` a milestone soon to be accomplished.'' The V-22 Osprey performed both a slow taxi liftoff and a vertical takeoff during the landmark maneuvers and made conventional `` run-on'' landings, the officials said. Its top speed during the tests was limited to 20 knots, less than 25 mph. The aircraft combines the operational capabilities of a helicopter with those of a fixed-wind turboprop. With its engines and prop-rotors vertical, the V-22 takes off, hovers and lands like a helicopter. With its prop-rotors in forward position, the Osprey would become a fast, fuel-efficient, high-altitude turboprop airplane capable of reaching speeds of more than 345 mph. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> Helicopters President <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesnut </PERSON> said the Osprey gives the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military `` the ability to develop new missions and tactics that can not be accomplished by any existing helicopter or airplane.'' Six flight-test prototypes are being built by <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> Helicopters of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, under a $ 1.8 billion full-scale development contract issued by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Air Systems Command. The versatile Osprey is the first modern weapons system designed from conception to meet requirements of all four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed services, with deliveries expected to begin in 1992.
