<HEAD>Japanese Entrepreneur Dies Of Respiratory Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> and a leader in one of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest business conglomerates, died of respiratory failure early Monday. He was 72. <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON>, a 1940 graduate of the Economics Department at <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, in 1959 became president of the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a railway that was the core of the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyu </ORGANIZATION> business group his father founded. <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON> joined <ORGANIZATION> Tokyu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in October 1945 after serving in the Japanese army. Under <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON>'s guidance, the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyu </ORGANIZATION> business group expanded to 334 firms, including railways, real estate and construction firms, department stores and hotels. <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON>, who sustained an interest in pan-Pacific economic cooperation, served since 1978 as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> PBEC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, a forum of 850 company representatives from 16 countries and areas, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. In 1984, he was elected head of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and Industry. He retired from the post in December 1987 for health reasons and became an honorary president. <PERSON> Gotoh </PERSON> had been in and out of hospitals since he underwent surgery for a stomach ulcer in May 1987. Gotoh is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Yoko </PERSON>, three sons and two daughters.
