<FIRST>r f AM-Bronco-Samurai Bjt   03-19 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bronco-Samurai, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bronco, Not Samurai, Feels Heat Of Government Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It would be hard to tell from the amount of media coverage that the vehicle under government investigation for rollovers is the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bronco </ORGANIZATION> II and not the <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Samurai </PERSON>. It would also be hard to tell from the sales totals. Although the government has never had a harsh word about the Samurai, its sales are a tenth what they were before Consumer Reports magazine charged last year that the boxy little four-wheel-drive vehicle tips over too easily. The fate of the Samurai illustrates the power of the news media to influence car-buying decisions, particularly the power of the repeatedly televised videotapes showing the Samurai going up on two wheels in high-speed maneuvers. Now <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is waiting to see what will happen to sales of its <ORGANIZATION> Bronco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION> following the announcement last week that it will be investigated for rollovers by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Most auto analysts predict the government's probe _ strictly speaking, an engineering analysis _ will have little effect on Bronco II sales, for two reasons: _ Engineering analyses are routine Fifty-five were under way as of the end of February, the agency says. Of those, only some go on to the next stage, the `` case level.'' And only some of those result in determinations of safety defects. _ The Bronco II has not received as much negative publicity as the Samurai got, partly because the government did not release any gripping videotapes of the Bronco II going up on two wheels `` The power of the press really hit home in the Samurai controversy. So far the Bronco is pretty far from that type of situation,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Merlis </PERSON>, an auto analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The Jeep-like Samurai was rolling along at sales of about 6,000 a month when Consumer Reports magazine called a news conference on June 2 to say it was giving the vehicle a not-acceptable rating. It said the Japanese-built Samurai `` literally trips over its own feet'' because of a narrow tread width, short wheelbase, light weight and high center of gravity. Sales plunged to 2,199 in June. <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> responded with dealer incentives that resulted in sharp price cuts, and sales rebounded to 6,327 in July and a record 12,208 in August. The automaker appeared to have come back from the brink. It got a boost on Sept. 1 when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> denied a recall petition by the Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based consumer group. The respite was short-lived, though, as sales plummeted to 560 in September, 787 in October and 483 in November. They jumped to 2,483 in December before retreating to 263 in January and 472 in February. Sales of the bigger, heavier and more expensive Bronco II run about 9,000 to 11,000 a month. Officials of <LOCATION> Brea </LOCATION>, Calif.-based American <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> say Samurai sales have been hampered by several unrelated factors, including the difficulties of introducing three other <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> models in the past several months: the Sidekick, the Swift GTi and the Swift GLX. But they admit that last summer's publicity hurt. Sales of all four <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> vehicles combined totaled less than 3,000 last month. `` We have seen a longer-term impact on the sales than we would have hoped. I'm not sure there is one reporter who can write a story about <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> without mentioning this issue,'' said <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doll </PERSON>, a spokeswoman with the company's public relations agency, <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. The government safety board said it chose to investigate the Bronco II because statistics unearthed last year showed it had a far higher rate of fatal rollovers than the Samurai. <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Ditlow </PERSON>, head of the Center for Auto Safety, said he thinks the government missed some fatal rollovers involving the Samurai while slightly overstating the Bronco II's. He says the vehicles are equally bad. `` They both deserve to be investigated,'' he said in an interview last week. In fact, the government probe may not make much difference. Unless the agency discovers serious rollover problems with the Bronco II, its sales are likely to remain healthy. For the Samurai, meanwhile, the damage is already done.
</TEXT>
