<FIRST>u f AM-TickerTalk Bjt   03-19 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ticker Talk, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerage Chief Urges New Twist for IRAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top Wall Street executive has begun a campaign for a measure he says would stimulate savings without aggravating the government's budget problems. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON>, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, contends that his idea would `` put some renewed sex appeal'' into individual retirement accounts. At the same time, he says, it would help to pay in advance for the future costs of health care and the well-being of the rapidly growing numbers of older Americans. <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON>'s idea, put forward in speeches he has been giving this month, is not to restore the tax breaks for <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> contributions that were curtailed by the Tax Reform Act of 1986 _ not right away, at least. Rather, he is proposing that <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> savers be given the right to withdraw money from their accounts in the future for certain purposes _ medical, educational and home ownership _ without having to pay tax on the proceeds. <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON>'s argument starts from the premise that the nation needs to increase its chronically low savings rate if it is going to be able to bear the costs of supporting an aging population in the decades ahead. But he also acknowledges a more immediate need to settle current accounts that are out of whack. `` The deficit crisis is real,'' he says. `` We've got to find ways to encourage increased savings that take little or nothing out of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s hide now.'' Of course, <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON> is hardly a disinterested party in the debate over tax policy. When IRAs were opened up to all working Americans in 1982, they became lucrative products for firms like <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, when deductions for contributions ended for married couples making $ 50,000 or more a year, and individuals with incomes of $ 35,000 and up, the flow of money into these accounts slowed significantly. But does his idea have merit? At first glance, at least, it looks like a tax break that would benefit upper-income people the most. Hence, it would n't seem to have much chance of attracting support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. However, supporters of the idea point out, the situation is n't quite that simple All <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> withdrawals, except for the amount of non-deductible contributions made by the well-to-do, are now subject to tax. So under <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON>'s proposal, all American workers would have a greater incentive to put as much money as possible in IRAs. The interest, dividends and capital gains that now build up tax-free inside IRAs would remain tax-free when they were taken out. What's more, the accounts could be used to plan not just for retirement, but for other goals <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON> describes as socially desirable, including education, and to help shoulder the burden of the mounting cost of health care. But the idea raises several tough questions. First of all, what would it mean for future government budgets? If taxpayers were able to build up large new amounts of money that the government could lay no claim to, might tax rates on other income have to be raised, and new types of taxes be created? Furthermore, would <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> contributors totally buy the idea that their money could actually never be taxed? Recent tax changes have tainted principles that once were thought to be sacrosanct: For example, `` no taxes on taxes.'' Well, state sales taxes no longer are deductible and the deduction for state income taxes barely survived the last debate about changing the rules. <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON>'s case is that the nation should be thinking long-term in handling its finances. As legions of financial advisers have pointed out in recent years, that is hard to do in a climate where the tax rules are subject to frequent and seemingly limitless change.
</TEXT>
