<SECOND>AM-Channel One, Bjt,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Begins Research to Build Case for TV News Show for Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students at two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> high schools, <PERSON> Gahr </PERSON> and nearby <LOCATION> Cerritos </LOCATION>, took a current events quiz last week, and the results could help decide whether commercial television gets a place in the classroom. The quizzes were part of a research effort designed to see if a daily TV news show that includes paid advertising is helping students learn. The nearly 2,000 students at <ORGANIZATION> Gahr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cerritos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, have been able to watch the news show called Channel One for the past two weeks on 91 new television sets given to the school and installed in every classroom. The youngsters at <ORGANIZATION> Cerritos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, whose enrollment numbers and characteristics resemble those of its suburban <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> neighbor, have n't had a chance to see the news show but agreed to take the quiz anyway. <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, Tenn.-based media concern that developed Channel One, plans to tally the results from these schools along with those from tests at the five other schools in the Channel One project and their sister schools and see if the show is helping educate students. Backers of the program are betting that the research will show a significant difference in the results from the schools that have been exposed to the show and those that have not. That could be a critical element in Whittle's efforts to persuade other schools to sign up for the Channel One project. Whittle hopes to expand the service to as many as 8,000 schools nationwide in the fall of 1990. `` We expect to see real differences, and if we do it will be a real plus for the program,'' Whittle chairman <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said Friday in a telelphone interview. The main obstacle to the project appears to be the intense opposition from children's advocates and some education groups who say companies should not be allowed to pitch their products to an essentially captive audience in school. Groups such as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secondary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principals </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parent-Teacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> have opposed it. <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Charren </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, a Massachusetts-based children's advocacy group, said she thinks the Channel One test has been orchestrated to gloss over the bad precedent she says is being set of allowing commercials in classrooms. `` The problem is we are selling children to advertisers ... They think they are going to get enough kids buying enough products to make the investment worthwhile,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Charren </PERSON> said. The test of Channel One began March 6 at <LOCATION> Gahr </LOCATION> and five others schools _ <ORGANIZATION> Mumford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Withrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eisenhower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Billerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>. Each school was given about $ 50,000 in televisions, video recorders and a satellite dish to recieve a daily 12-minute news show with up to two minutes of paid ads. The sponsors include <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>'s jeans, Snickers candy bars and Clearasil acne cream In return, the schools are asked to play the show once each school day. The test is to include five weeks of programs over a seven-week period. Channel One has just begun a two-week hiatus for spring break during which the producers hope to fine-tune the program. A typical news show relates the day's top stories and contains features on subjects like the environment and the lifetsyles of Soviet teen-agers. Last week, Channel One also carried a live 15-minute special without commercials on the launch of the space shuttle Discovery. To test if the show is effective, Whittle plans to give quizzes at all six schools and their sister schools in each district for comparison. Students at <LOCATION> Gahr </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cerritos </LOCATION> got 29 multiple choice questions, most of which came from information in the past week's shows. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said his company is also conducting two other types of studies to measure the effectiveness of the project. He said one involves group interviews with teachers or students from the schools. The other involves telephone interviews with students who have gotten their parent's permission to talk about the commercials on the program. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said the comparative quiz results, the group discussions and the telephone polling will all figure in whether his company invests more than $ 100 million in hardware alone that he said will be required to go national. `` Five weeks is n't a very long time, but we ought to be able to show some movement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
