<SECOND>AM-Futures-Warning, Bjt,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Leaders Return Home With Congressional Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the futures industry returned home from their annual convention in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with sunburns and a stinging admonition from some concerned congressmen to clean up their business. About two dozen federal lawmakers spoke during last week's four-day meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and their message to the approximately 1,000 brokers and exchange officials was clear: Put your house in order because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is coming through `` It is incumbent upon you to open your eyes to wrongdoing where it exists and be assertive and effective in rooting it out, even at the expense of making some internal fundamental changes; to try to do it yourself rather than waiting for someone else to do it to you,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., during a panel discussion on Saturday The futures industry is due for an official review as part of the congressional process for reauthorizing the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the federal agency that regulates futures trading. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s current 3-year authorization expires on Sept. 30. The recent disclosure of a sweeping <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation of suspected trading fraud at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s two world-leading futures exchanges has heightened public interest in the industry and brought demands for intense scrutiny and reform of these once-obscure markets. `` Out there in the country, our constituents do n't know a lot about futures trading; none of them have ever heard of the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>. It is important as we look at this industry that they know the importance of it,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tallon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, who sits on a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agriculture subcommittee that is conducting one of several congressional reviews of the industry. A future is a binding contract to buy or sell a bundle of commodities or financial instruments at a specified price at a future date. Agricultural commodity futures have been traded at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest futures exchange, for more than 140 years. But most of the action now is in financial futures, which were invented in the 1970s and are heavily used by institutional investors around the world to reduce their risks in the international stock, bond and currency markets. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s probe of suspected cheating by traders at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> has yielded no charges since it was revealed on Jan. 19. Nevertheless, some key lawmakers who attended last week's industry meeting in <LOCATION> Boca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, indicated support for: _ Beefing up <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s trade-surveillance and rule-enforcement _ Tightening up record-keeping by futures exchanges and brokerage firms _ Cracking down on certain trading practices that some believe provide opportunities to cheat If the futures industry can not satisfactorily police itself, several lawmakers implied, it will lose its cherished freedom to set and enforce most of its own rules. `` Our committee is not going to resolve in favor of self-regulation unless there is a perception that it seems to be working universally,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which also oversees futures regulation. Over and over during the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> meeting, exchange officials vowed to improve their auditing of trades and to root out and punish wrongdoers. `` Certainly we can do better than we have done,'' <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee, told <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> on Saturday. `` I give you the entire promise of my whole being that we will respond in every possible way that we can to your message.'' Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, suggested that futures leaders view the various investigations of their industry as an `` opportunity to recapture the one commodity you can never afford to lose: the universal recognition of the integrity of your markets.''
