<HEAD>Study: Boston Tenants Paying Highest Percentage of Income on Rent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The study...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with other
available cities (</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Boston-area tenants pay a bigger chunk of their income in rent than tenants in any other major city in the country, while <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> residents pay the smallest, a new study says. A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> research firm, <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advice </ORGANIZATION>, calculated that <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s median rent is $ 586 a month. That is about the same as <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, but the study found median incomes were lower in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, so that while <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Franciscans </LOCATION> pay 19.5 percent of their income on rent, Bostonians pay 21.3 percent. Renters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> pay a median of $ 444 per month. Though the rent is lower than <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s, it amounts to about the same percentage of income as renters in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> pay, again because <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> incomes are lower, the study found. The figures are lower than actual market-rate rents because they include subsidized apartments. Excluding subsidized apartments, the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Redevelopment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> figures the average rent in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> last year was $ 800 a month. <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> was ranked as the most economical of the 25 cities surveyed in terms of percentage of income, with a monthly rent of $ 346 _ about 13 percent of the median household income. It was followed by <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, where the median rent is $ 322, or 13.5 percent of household income. Next to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, the least economical city was <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where median rents were $ 521, or 20.7 percent of income. The average of all 25 cities was $ 425 _ 18.5 percent of monthly income. Median rents for other cities, along with the percentage that it comprised of median income, included <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, $ 380 and 13.8 percent; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, $ 441 and 15.1 percent; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, $ 419 and 15.3 percent; and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, $ 601 and 18.3 percent. The study touched a nerve in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, where rents have increased 64 percent since 1982. That includes a 6.1 percent rise last year that was the biggest of any major metropolitan area except <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. Rents are skyrocketing in a city that already has one of the highest median house prices in the nation, estimated as high as $ 195,000. `` The simple fact is that people ca n't afford to buy homes,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Finfer </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affordable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. `` So the average blue-collar, lower-middle-class person is staying in rentals longer, making more competition for rental units. There's not enough production of affordable housing.'' `` We've looked at some of the rent indexes, and the Northeast in general and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> in particular have had above-average rent increases over the past six to eight years,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Apgar </PERSON>, acting director of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Economists say the middle class is caught in a dilemma of not being able to save for a down payment because of high rents, but making too much money to qualify for subsidized rentals. Would-be homebuyers <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobey </PERSON> have been saving for a down payment for more than three years and expect it will take at least two more. `` House prices have risen so fast that it's terribly hard for first-time home buyers,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Robey </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuker </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said there is virtually no construction of rental apartments in the range just below <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s median level He said city leaders must try to work with community leaders in encouraging construction of affordable housing. `` Everyone's for affordable housing as long as it's not in their back yard,'' he said. `` There's a lot of lip service, but not a lot of action.''
