<HEAD>Judge Rules Against High Voltage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> welcomed Sunday a federal court ruling that upheld his company's defenses against a hostile $ 643 million takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voltage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` We are pleased with the court's decision,'' said <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the Milwaukee-based supplier of food and food ingredients. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadtmueller </PERSON> issued his ruling Saturday, denying a motion by a High Voltage that sought to invalidate <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s anti-takeover law. The judge also denied a motion for a preliminary injunction against <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION>'s `` poison pill'' defense against takeovers. That defense would allow Universal shareholders to buy additional shares of the company at half price if High Voltage were to pursue its bid. High Voltage said it had no immediate comment on the ruling. <PERSON> Stadtmueller </PERSON> rejected an argument that Universal's directors violated their duty to shareholders by opposing the takeover and threatening use of the poison pill. `` I find no evidence in the record which convinces me that the board failed to review this offer in a dispassionate and neutral manner,'' the judge wrote. High Voltage has offered $ 35 a share for Universal stock, which closed Friday at $ 33 in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. Universal executives contend a takeover would damage the company's long-term growth, including its ability to invest in research and development of new products. Universal, based in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, is a worldwide supplier of food and food ingredients, including yeast, cheese, frozen potatoes and food colorings. It employs about 4,600 people.
