<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Stock Prices Fall In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar firmed in early trading against the Japanese yen Monday while stock prices fell. The dollar opened trading at 131.88 yen, up 0.81 yen from Friday's close. A dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> said the dollar remained firm in early trading following a strong showing on overseas markets last Friday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the currency closed last week at 131.68 yen following a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government report Friday that the nation's producer price index rose a full percentage point in February, triggering a new wave of inflation and interest-rate worries. There was concern over higher short-term interest rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said the dealer who spoke anonymously. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 77.01-point loser last Friday, shed 315.24 points or 0.9 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 31,705.77.
